menu "Storage Eviction"

    config STORAGE_EVICTION_TARGET_PCT
        int "Free space trigger threshold in % of card capacity"
        range 1 50
        default 10
        help
            Low watermark for the SD card free space, as a percentage
            of the card's total formatted capacity. When free space
            falls below this threshold, an eviction pass starts and
            keeps deleting until free space reaches the high watermark
            (trigger + headroom). See STORAGE_EVICTION_HEADROOM_PCT.

            The computed value is clamped to a floor of 256 MiB and a
            ceiling of STORAGE_EVICTION_TARGET_MIB, so the watermarks
            scale down for small cards while large cards keep the
            classic fixed-watermark behavior.

    config STORAGE_EVICTION_TARGET_MIB
        int "Trigger threshold ceiling in MiB"
        default 1024
        help
            Upper bound for the capacity-derived trigger watermark.
            Whenever STORAGE_EVICTION_TARGET_PCT of the card's capacity
            exceeds this value, this value is used instead. With the
            defaults (10% capped at 1024 MiB) the ceiling binds from
            ~10 GiB of formatted capacity upward — in practice, cards
            advertised as 16 GB and larger.

    config STORAGE_EVICTION_HEADROOM_PCT
        int "Free space headroom in % of card capacity"
        range 1 90
        default 25
        help
            Hysteresis between the trigger threshold and the stop
            condition, as a percentage of the card's total formatted
            capacity. Once eviction starts (free < trigger), it keeps
            running until free >= trigger + headroom. A larger headroom
            means fewer eviction passes but each pass deletes more
            files.

            The computed value is clamped to a floor of 512 MiB and a
            ceiling of STORAGE_EVICTION_HEADROOM_MIB.

    config STORAGE_EVICTION_HEADROOM_MIB
        int "Headroom ceiling in MiB"
        default 4096
        help
            Upper bound for the capacity-derived headroom. Whenever
            STORAGE_EVICTION_HEADROOM_PCT of the card's capacity
            exceeds this value, this value is used instead. With the
            defaults (25% capped at 4096 MiB) the ceiling binds from
            16 GiB of formatted capacity upward — cards advertised as
            32 GB and larger reproduce the classic "keep ~5 GiB free"
            behavior.

    config STORAGE_EVICTION_MIN_CARD_SIZE_MIB
        int "Minimum SD card total size in MiB to enable eviction"
        default 1024
        help
            Eviction is skipped entirely on SD cards whose total
            capacity is smaller than this threshold. Because the
            watermarks scale with capacity, eviction is viable on any
            card comfortably larger than the watermark floors
            (256 + 512 MiB combined); below this threshold the stop
            watermark would eat most of the card, so the device just
            fills the card with downloads and then stops accepting new
            ones rather than churn the file system. Set to 0 to
            disable the guard entirely.

    config STORAGE_EVICTION_INITIAL_AGE_DAYS
        int "Initial age threshold in days"
        default 30
        help
            First eviction pass deletes files not accessed within
            this many days. If more space is needed, the threshold
            is halved on each subsequent pass.

    config STORAGE_EVICTION_MIN_AGE_HOURS
        int "Minimum age threshold in hours"
        default 4
        help
            Floor for the age threshold. Files accessed more recently
            than this are never deleted, even if the free space target
            has not been reached.

    config CHANNEL_EVICTION_AGE_DAYS
        int "Channel cache eviction age in days"
        default 60
        help
            Channel cache files (.cache, .json, .settings.json) that
            have not been loaded for playback within this many days
            are deleted. Channels in the active playset are always
            protected regardless of age.

endmenu
